Author: Christopher Dannemiller <cdannemiller@nvidia.com>
Date:   Mon Apr 27 13:59:50 2026 -0700

    vkd3d: Collapse va_map RTAS dual-output to single handle + kind.

    vkd3d_va_map_try_read_rtas and vkd3d_va_map_try_place_rtas encoded
    the AS-vs-OMM kind by populating one of two same-typed
    VkAccelerationStructureKHR out-params. The dual encoding existed
    because OMM was VkMicromapEXT pre-KHR - different Vulkan handle types
    made the slot choice meaningful. Post-KHR plus the GENERIC view-create
    work, both kinds are the same handle type at the same union slot, and
    the encoding is just an awkward way to communicate a boolean.

    Replace with a single handle out-param plus an explicit bool
    *is_micromap. vkd3d_va_map_place_opacity_micromap folds into
    vkd3d_va_map_place_acceleration_structure with a new bool rtas_is_omm
    parameter; the static _try_place_rtas helper goes away.

    The merged place function mutates the cached rtas_is_micromap on
    cross-kind reuse, so the field is widened from bool to uint32_t
    accessed via vkd3d_atomic_uint32_* with relaxed ordering. D3D12
    applications can free a structure at a VA and rebuild a different-
    kind structure on the same address; the cached tag must follow.
    Relaxed is sufficient because no other state synchronizes on this
    flag, and the handle slot is shared between kinds (a reader seeing a
    stale tag still dereferences a valid AS). Pre-publish initialization
    in vkd3d_create_*_view stays as a plain store, synchronized to later
    readers by the view_map spinlock release.

    The two cross-kind FIXMEs (RTAS-on-OMM and OMM-on-RTAS) consolidate
    into a single unified FIXME on cross-kind reuse; the underlying
    behavior is safe but the diagnostic helps catch app-side
    build-without-rebuild bugs.

    Postbuild and copy dispatchers in acceleration_structure.c and
    command.c switch from the dual-out + which-was-populated branch to
    the single-handle + boolean branch.

    Signed-off-by: Christopher Dannemiller <cdannemiller@nvidia.com>
