commit e72c07531baacafd0e3c562df2bcd750dab204bd
Author: Will Campbell <wcampbell@nvidia.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 21 07:26:32 2026 -0400

    Adjust VK_NV_low_latency2 usage so downstream components can map vkQueuePresent calls to the corresponding low latency frame id (#2938)

    * Adjust VK_NV_low_latency2 usage so downstream components can map vkQueuePresent calls to the corresponding low latency frame id.

    Motivation: In order to measure latency statistics in applications integrating NVIDIA Reflex
    we need to map vkQueuePresent calls to the corresponding low latency frame id.
    We can then measure latency from the SIMULATION_START marker to the time at which the
    vkQueuePresent lands (queried from VK_EXT_present_timing).
    This can be done in native applications by looking for PRESENT_START and _END
    markers surrounding the present call, but vkd3d-proton interferes with this by deferring
    present calls to a background thread.

    This change has vkd3d-proton submit OUT_OF_BAND_PRESENT markers on the background
    thread surrounding the vkQueuePresent call with the appropriate low latency frame id
    for the frame. We get the frame id by looking at the latency markers surrounding the app's
    DXGI present call.

    This change also simplifies the VkPresentIdKHR selection logic, no longer attemping
    to align the present id to the low latency frame id. This frame attribution scheme does
    not work with DLSS Frame Generation, which will submit multiple OUT_OF_BAND presents
    with the same low latency frame id. This contradicts the VK_NV_low_latency2 spec
    but will work fine in practice as the NVIDIA driver has always treated these as separate IDs.
    We plan to make this explicit in a future revision of the VK_NV_low_latency2 spec.

    This change should have no functional impact with today's drivers.

    TESTING:
        Tested with a Vulkan layer that prints latency statistics by attributing
        vkQueuePresent calls to low latency frame IDs as follows:
          - When vkQueuePresent is called in between OUT_OF_BAND_PRESENT_START and _END markers,
            use their frame id. (vkd3d-proton will always take this path)
          - Otherwise take the frame id of the most recent PRESENT_START marker that has not
            already been mapped to a vkQueuePresent call. (vkd3d-proton mirrors this logic during
            the DXGI present call to determine the frame id)
          - If no such marker exists then Reflex is off or not implemented correctly,
            this latency measurement scheme is not possible.

        Saw reasonable results in several titles with various combinations of Reflex on and off, DLSS-FG
        and NVIDIA Smooth Motion.
            - Cyberpunk 2077, Arc Raiders and Dying Light 2

        Also tested in some Vulkan native titles to confirm this vkQueuePresent to latency marker
        mapping scheme works there as well.

    * Remove VKD3D_LOW_LATENCY_FRAME_ID_STRIDE
